const Q_ECONOMICS_1991=[{"id": "objective>Economics>1991>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In market economy, the question of what, how and for whom to produce are solved by the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elected representative</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">planning committee</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">price mechanism</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">government</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The price mechanism, also known as the market mechanism, is an essential feature of market economies. It is based on the interaction of supply and demand in determining prices and allocating resources. In this system, prices are determined through the forces of supply and demand in the marketplace. Producers and consumers make decisions based on these prices, which guide them in determining what goods and services to produce, how to produce them, and for whom to produce them.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Economic goods are termed scarce goods when they are?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not available in sufficient quantities to satisfy all wants for them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not produced in sufficient quantities to satisfy the effective demand for them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of high quality</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of primary importance in satisfying the needs of a society</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In economics, scarcity refers to the limited availability of resources relative to the unlimited wants and needs of individuals and society. When economic goods, which are goods that have value and are scarce, are not available in sufficient quantities to fulfill all the desires or demands for them, they are considered scarce goods. This means that there is a shortage or limited supply of these goods relative to the demand or wants of individuals.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : BASIC CONCEPT OF ECONOMICS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A school girl  who needs a book and mirror, each costing five naira, decides to purchase the book instead of the mirror since she cannot pay for the two at the same time. Determine the real cost of her book</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The five naira she spent on the book</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Five naira real cash value</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The mirror</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The book</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In this scenario, if the school girl chooses to purchase the book instead of the mirror due to budget constraints, the opportunity cost or the real cost of the book would indeed be the mirror. By deciding to buy the book, she is giving up the opportunity to purchase the mirror.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : OPPORTUNITY COST"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macroeconomics is a study of economics science from he point of view of?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resources markets or production units</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individual producers or consumers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">aggregate or general economy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">companies or individual firms</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macroeconomics focuses on the behavior, performance, and structure of an entire economy as a whole. It examines the overall economic indicators, such as national income, employment, inflation, and economic growth, to understand how the economy functions and how different sectors interact with each other. Macroeconomics analyzes the broader factors that impact the economy, such as government policies, fiscal and monetary measures, and international trade.</div>", "topic": "EQUILIBRIUM LEVEL OF NATIONAL INCOME : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If units of a variable factor are increasingly added to a fixed factor and the marginal physical product keeps increasing, production is said to be taking place under conditions of?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increasing returns to the variable factor</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increasing returns to scale</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">constant returns to variable factor</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">external economies of scale</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Increasing returns to the variable factor occur when the addition of each additional unit of the variable factor leads to a proportionally larger increase in output. In other words, the marginal physical product (MPP) of the variable factor increases as more units of it are added to the fixed factor.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRODUCTION : LAWS OF PRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At any given level of output, the total cost of a firm equals the?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal cost plus the average cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fixed cost less its variable cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">average cost multiplied by variable costs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">economic costs multiplied by variable costs</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Total cost is the sum of all costs incurred by a firm in producing a given level of output. It consists of both fixed costs and variable costs. Average cost is the total cost divided by the quantity of output, representing the average cost per unit of production. Variable costs are costs that vary with the level of output. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, to determine the total cost, you multiply the average cost by the variable costs. This is because the average cost represents the per-unit cost, and when multiplied by the quantity of output, it gives the total cost. Variable costs account for the portion of costs that change with the level of production.</div>", "topic": "THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At any given level of output, a firm's total variable cost equals?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total cost less marginal cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total cost less total fixed costs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total cost less average cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">average variable cost and marginal cost</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">These are expenses that remain constant regardless of the production level. Examples include rent, salaries of administrative staff, etc. <br/>  <br/> TVC = TC - TFC <br/>  <br/> This formula highlights that total variable cost is what's left of the total cost after removing the portion that doesn't vary with production volume (total fixed cost).</div>", "topic": "THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If the price of a ball point pen falls from #1.00 to #0.60 and the quantity demanded increases from 200 to 300, the point elasticity of demand is equal to?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.25</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.80</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.50</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.40</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">E = (percentage change in quantity demanded) / (percentage change in price) x 100 <br/>  <br/> Step 1: Calculate Percentage Changes <br/> Percentage change in quantity demanded: <br/> Quantity change = (New quantity - Old quantity) / Old quantity  x 100 <br/> = (300 - 200 ) / 200    x100 <br/> = 100  / 200   x 100 <br/> = 50% <br/>  <br/> Percentage change in price: <br/> Price change = (New price - Old price) / Old price  x100 <br/> = (0.60 - 1.00) / 1.00  x100 <br/> = -0.40 / 1.00  x 100 (Note the negative sign for a price decrease) <br/> = -40% <br/>  <br/> Step 2: Apply the formula <br/> E = (50) / (-40) <br/> = -1.25  (The negative sign indicates an elastic demand, where quantity demanded changes more than proportionally to the price change.) <br/>  <br/> Since we typically focus on the absolute value of elasticity, the answer is 1.25.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If a society is operating on the production possibility curve, this implies that the resources are?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fully and efficiently utilized</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fully but inefficiently utilized</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">efficiency but not fully utilized </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abundant</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This curve illustrates the various combinations of two goods or services a society can produce with its limited resources and technology. Points on the PPC represent achievable production levels, while points outside represent unattainable combinations due to resource limitations. <br/> Full Utilization: Operating on the PPC implies that all available resources are being used in production. There's no idleness or underutilization of resources. <br/> Efficiency: Being on the PPC also indicates that resources are being used efficiently. This means no good or service is being produced at a higher cost (in terms of sacrificed production of the other good) than necessary.</div>", "topic": "INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : PRODUCTION POSSIBILITY CURVE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A market is in disequilibrium if?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the quantity purchased is greater than quantity sold</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the quantity sold differs from the quantity purchased</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at a lower price, a large quantity is sold</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the quantity demand differs from the quantity supplied</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a well-functioning market, equilibrium is the ideal state where the quantity demanded by buyers exactly matches the quantity supplied by sellers for a particular good or service at a specific price. This creates a balance where there's no pressure for prices to change. <br/>  <br/> Disequilibrium, on the other hand, arises when this balance is disrupted.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The cross -elasticity of demand between complementary goods is?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unitary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">positive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">zero</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">negative</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This concept measures how the quantity demanded for one good (good A) changes in response to a price change in another good (good B). <br/> Complementary goods: These are goods that are consumed together and derive their demand from each other. For instance, printers and printer cartridges are complementary goods. <br/> When the price of one complementary good increases, the demand for the other good typically decreases. This is because consumers are less likely to purchase one good (e.g., printer) if the price of the good used with it (e.g., toner) becomes more expensive. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, the cross-elasticity of demand between complementary goods is negative. A price increase in one good leads to a decrease in the quantity demanded of the other good.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Resources are efficiently allocated when production takes place at that output where price equals</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal revenue</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">average variable cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal cost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total cost</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Efficient allocation of resources occurs when production takes place at the output level where the price equals the marginal cost. This is because the marginal cost represents the additional cost incurred by producing one more unit of a good or service. When the price equals the marginal cost, it indicates that the benefit gained from producing one more unit (the price) is equal to the cost of producing that additional unit (the marginal cost). This equilibrium ensures that resources are allocated efficiently, maximizing overall welfare in the economy.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : PERFECT MARKET"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Comparison of the price and output decisions of a perfectly competitive firm with those of a monopolist shows that the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopolist charges a lower price that the perfect competitor</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perfect competitor charges a lower price and produces a large output than the monopolist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perfect competitor produces a smaller output than the monopolist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">monopolist charges a lower price and produces a larger output than the perfect competitor</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a perfectly competitive market, there are numerous firms that are price takers, meaning they have no control over the market price. Each firm produces a small portion of the total market supply, and as a result, the firm's output decision has no impact on the market price. Consequently, a perfectly competitive firm charges a price equal to the market price. <br/>  <br/> On the other hand, a monopolist is the sole supplier in the market, giving them the ability to have some control over the price. A monopolist can set the price they charge for their product because there are no close substitutes available from other suppliers. In order to maximize their profits, a monopolist will typically set the price higher than the marginal cost of production. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, a perfect competitor charges a lower price compared to a monopolist because they are price takers and have no control over the market price. Additionally, a perfect competitor also produces a larger output because they do not have the market power to restrict production like a monopolist does.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET-MONOPOLY~~MARKET STRUCTURE : PERFECT MARKET"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a perfectly competitive market, the firm is in long-run equilibrium at the output where</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal cost is minimum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">average cost is minimum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total cost is minimum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal cost revenue is maximum</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a perfectly competitive market, a firm is in long-run equilibrium when it produces at the output level where its average cost is minimum. This condition ensures that the firm is operating efficiently and maximizing its profitability. <br/>  <br/> The average cost is calculated by dividing the total cost by the quantity of output produced. It represents the cost per unit of production. When a firm is in long-run equilibrium, it has chosen the optimal scale of production that minimizes the average cost. <br/>  <br/> If the firm were producing at an output level where the average cost is above the minimum point, it would indicate that there is room for cost reduction by adjusting the scale of production. On the other hand, if the firm were producing at an output level where the average cost is below the minimum point, it would mean that the firm could increase its scale of production to further minimize costs and improve profitability</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : PERFECT MARKET"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ordinary partner in a partnership</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">takes no active in the management of the business</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has limited liability in case of business failure</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has unlimited liability in case of business failure</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cannot be sued personally on matters relating to the business</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a partnership, there are two types of partners: general partners and limited partners. The ordinary partner, also known as a general partner, has unlimited liability in case of business failure. <br/>  <br/> Unlimited liability means that the general partner is personally responsible for the debts and obligations of the partnership. If the partnership fails to meet its financial obligations, creditors can go after the personal assets of the general partner to satisfy the debts. This includes seizing personal property, bank accounts, and other assets to cover the partnership's liabilities.</div>", "topic": "BUSINESS ORGANISATION : PARTNERSHIP"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A possible factor which limits the extent of growth of a firm is the?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">existence of a monopoly</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bureaucratic delays in decision-making</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">use of by-products</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unwillingness to share ownership and control</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A possible factor that limits the extent of growth of a firm is the unwillingness to share ownership and control. This refers to situations where the owners or management of a firm are hesitant or resistant to involve external investors or partners in the ownership and decision-making processes. <br/>  <br/> When a firm is unwilling to share ownership and control, it can face limitations in accessing additional capital, expertise, and resources that could facilitate its growth. By not seeking outside investments or partnerships, the firm may struggle to expand its operations, invest in new projects or technologies, or enter new markets.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRODUCTION : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the most outstanding disadvantages of co-operative societies as a business organization is that?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">true spirit of co-operation is marred by the delegated authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">members show much interest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is poorly financed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">membership interest is centred on sharing of essential commodities</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a co-operative society, members come together voluntarily to pool their resources and work collectively for their mutual benefit. The true essence of a cooperative is based on principles such as democratic control, equal participation, and shared decision-making. However, as the cooperative grows in size or complexity, it may become necessary to delegate authority and decision-making to a smaller group or elected board of directors. <br/>  <br/> This delegation of authority can sometimes lead to a loss of the true spirit of cooperation within the organization. Members may feel that their voices are not adequately heard, or that decisions are made without their full participation. This can create a sense of detachment or disengagement among the members, diminishing the cooperative's sense of community and shared ownership.</div>", "topic": "BUSINESS ORGANISATION : CO-OPERATIVE SOCIETIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A disadvantage of a joint-stock company is?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unlimited liability</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">limited liability</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">continuity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loss of controlling interest</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a joint-stock company, ownership is divided into shares or stock, which can be bought and sold by shareholders. The ownership of the company is proportional to the number of shares held. This means that as new shareholders acquire shares or existing shareholders sell their shares, the ownership structure of the company can change. <br/>  <br/> One of the potential disadvantages of this ownership structure is the possibility of losing controlling interest. As more shares are sold to external investors or shareholders, the original founders or major shareholders may find their percentage of ownership reduced. This can result in a loss of control and influence over the company's decision-making processes.</div>", "topic": "BUSINESS ORGANISATION : LIMITED LIABILITY COMPANIES"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A characteristic of a debenture  is that?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its yield is based on profits</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its yield is a fixed rate of interest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its has no redemption date</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is no voting right when interest is paid</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A debenture is a type of long-term debt instrument issued by a company or government entity to raise funds. It is a form of borrowing where the issuer promises to repay the principal amount along with regular interest payments to the debenture holders. <br/>  <br/> The yield of a debenture refers to the return or interest rate that debenture holders receive on their investment. Unlike equity shares, which may have variable dividends based on profits, the yield of a debenture is typically fixed. When the debenture is issued, the interest rate or yield is specified, and it remains constant throughout the life of the debenture.</div>", "topic": "FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Industries tend to be located closer to market centres than to the sources of major raw materials if the?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">products are relatively cheap to transport to market centers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">products are relatively more expensive to transport than the major raw materials</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">raw materials are bulky</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">raw materials can also be imported</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This phenomenon is known as the \"weight-losing\" or \"bulk-reducing\" nature of industries. It occurs when the finished products are bulkier or heavier compared to the raw materials required for their production.When the products have a higher transportation cost compared to the major raw materials, it becomes more cost-effective to locate the industries closer to the market centers. This strategic decision minimizes the overall transportation costs by reducing the distance between the production site and the consumers. <br/>  <br/> If the products are relatively cheap to transport to market centers (option A), there would be less incentive to locate the industries closer to the market centers. The lower transportation cost would allow industries to be located farther away from the market centers without significant cost disadvantages.</div>", "topic": "INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One disadvantage of trade by barter is that?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">people are happier when they exchange the same quantities of goods through the medium of money rather than by barter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the person wishing to buy good X may not have good Y which is what the other wants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">one person must always be cheated when trade takes place by barter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it increases the initial cost of producing goods</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One disadvantage of trade by barter is that the person wishing to buy a specific good (X) may not possess the specific good (Y) that the other party wants in exchange. Barter involves the direct exchange of goods or services without the use of money as a medium of exchange. Instead, individuals trade goods or services directly with each other. <br/>  <br/> In a barter system, the lack of a common medium of exchange like money can create difficulties when there is a mismatch in the goods or services desired by the trading parties. If someone wants to acquire a particular item but does not possess a good or service that the other party desires in return, the trade cannot take place. This lack of coincidence of wants can lead to transactional challenges and hinder trade.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the function of Development Banks is to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mint money for the development of the economy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provide short-term loans to commercial banks</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provide medium and long-term finance for the development of the banking system</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provide medium and long-term finance for the development of the economy</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Development Banks are specialized financial institutions that are established with the primary objective of promoting economic development and growth. They play a crucial role in providing financial support to various sectors of the economy, particularly in developing countries. <br/>  <br/> These banks focus on providing medium and long-term financing, which means they offer loans and financial assistance with extended repayment periods. This type of financing is essential for undertaking large-scale development projects, such as infrastructure development, industrial expansion, agricultural projects, and other initiatives that require substantial investment over an extended period.</div>", "topic": "FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : DEVELOPMENT, MERCHANT, MORTGAGE BANK ETC"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To perform its function as a store of wealth and standard for deferred payment, money must be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">portable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in attractive form</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stable in value</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spent more on capital goods than on consumer goods</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Money serves as a medium of exchange, a unit of account, a store of wealth, and a standard for deferred payment. When money is used as a store of wealth, individuals and businesses hold money to preserve the value of their savings or assets over time. Additionally, money can be used for deferred payments, such as when loans are made or contracts are entered into with future payment obligations. <br/>  <br/> In order for money to effectively serve as a store of wealth and a standard for deferred payment, it must maintain its value over time. If the value of money fluctuates significantly or experiences rapid inflation or deflation, it undermines its ability to retain purchasing power or accurately represent deferred payment obligations. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, stability in value is a crucial characteristic for money to fulfill its functions as a store of wealth and standard for deferred payment.</div>", "topic": "MONEY : FUNCTIONS OF MONEY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fiduciary issue is that part of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the issue of notes backed entirely by gold</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a country's currency which is not negotiable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the issue of notes not backed by gold </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a country's currency officially issued</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fiduciary issue refers to the issuance of notes or currency that is not backed by gold or any other specific tangible asset. Instead, fiduciary issue relies on the trust and confidence in the issuing authority, typically a central bank or government, to maintain the value and stability of the currency. <br/>  <br/> In a fiduciary issue, the value of the currency is derived from the trust and belief that it can be exchanged for goods and services in the economy. The issuing authority is responsible for managing the money supply, maintaining price stability, and instilling confidence in the currency's value.</div>", "topic": "MONEY : TYPES OF MONEY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An effect of inflation is that it?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discourages trade by barter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">favours debtors at the expenses of creditors</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increases the real income of salary earners</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increases the value of a country's exports</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Inflation refers to the sustained increase in the general price level of goods and services in an economy over time. When inflation occurs, the purchasing power of money decreases, meaning that the same amount of money can buy fewer goods and services.</div>", "topic": "INFLATION & DEFLATION : EFFECT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Banks aid economic expansion and development by?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being very strict in lending policies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mobilizing savings for investment lending</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">paying interest on deposit accounts</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">charging high interest on loans</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Banks play a crucial role in the economy by serving as financial intermediaries between savers and borrowers. They collect deposits from individuals and businesses and then use those funds to provide loans and credit to borrowers, including individuals, businesses, and governments. <br/>  <br/> By mobilizing savings, banks channel funds from savers who have surplus funds to borrowers who need capital for various purposes, such as starting or expanding businesses, investing in infrastructure projects, or funding other developmental initiatives. This process of intermediation helps to allocate capital efficiently and promote economic growth.</div>", "topic": "FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : COMMERCIAL BANKS"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term \"Stock of Capital' means?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">amount of money necessary to start a business</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total amount receivable by all factors of production</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">amount of equipment plant and inventory existing at a time</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total amount available for economic development</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term \"Stock of Capital\" refers to the amount of equipment, plant, and inventory that exists at a particular time. It represents the tangible assets and physical infrastructure that are used in the production process. <br/>  <br/> The stock of capital includes machinery, buildings, tools, vehicles, technology, and other physical assets that are employed by businesses to produce goods and services. It represents the accumulated result of past investment in productive assets.</div>", "topic": "THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A tax that takes an increasing fraction of income as income goes down is called?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conditional</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">regressive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">progressive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">proportional</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A regressive tax system is one in which the tax rate increases as income decreases.  <br/>  <br/> Under a regressive tax system, the tax rates are structured in a way that imposes a higher tax burden on individuals with low income. As income decreases, the tax rate increases.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE : PRINCIPLE OF TAXATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Budget deficit is the amount by which?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total expenditure exceeds revenue</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recurrent expenditure exceeds revenue</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">capital expenditure exceeds revenue</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">recurrent expenditure exceeds capital expenditure</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A budget deficit occurs when a government's total expenditures, including both recurrent and capital expenditures, exceed its total revenue, such as tax collections and other sources of income. It represents a shortfall or negative balance in the government's budget.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE : BUDGET"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The average tax rate is defined as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total tax rate less the marginal tax rate</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the tax rate which applies to additional value income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the ratio of total taxes paid to total income</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marginal tax rate for being progressive</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The average tax rate is calculated by dividing the total amount of taxes paid by an individual or entity by their total income. It represents the average proportion of income that is paid in taxes.</div>", "topic": "PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Personal distribution of income implies?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the way in which income is distributed among specific households or spending units</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the distribution of income according to basic resources</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dividing income according to industries</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dividing income between personal taxes, consumption expenditures and savings</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Personal distribution of income refers to the way in which income is distributed among specific households or spending units within a population.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the advantages of international trade is that it?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increases world output</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encourages economic independence among nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restricts spread of technical knowledge</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">promotes self-reliance and satisfaction with only what can be produced internally</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">International trade allows countries to specialize in the production of goods and services in which they have a comparative advantage, meaning they can produce those goods more efficiently or at a lower opportunity cost compared to other countries. By specializing and trading with other nations, countries can expand their total output and benefit from increased efficiency and productivity. <br/>  <br/> Through international trade, countries can access a broader range of goods and services that may not be available or may be more expensive to produce domestically. This leads to an increase in the overall availability of goods and services, contributing to higher world output.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There is an improvement in the terms of trade of a country if?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a large quantity of exports is given up to obtain a unit of imports</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the volume of exports is greater than the volume of imports</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a smaller quantity of exports is given up to obtain a unit of imports</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the value of exports is greater than the value of imports</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">There is an improvement in the terms of trade of a country when a smaller quantity of exports is given up to obtain a unit of imports. <br/>  <br/> The terms of trade refer to the ratio at which a country can exchange its exports for imports. When the terms of trade improve, it means that a country can acquire a greater quantity of imports for a given quantity of exports.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE : TERMS OF TRADE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Under flexible exchange rates, a deficit could be corrected by?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">freezing the gold point</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appreciation of other currencies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">removing export subsidies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">removing tariffs</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Flexible exchange rates refer to a system where the exchange rates between currencies are determined by market forces of supply and demand. In this system, the value of a currency can fluctuate freely in response to changes in market conditions. <br/>  <br/> When a country has a trade deficit, it means that its imports exceed its exports, resulting in a negative balance of trade. To correct this deficit, the country's currency can appreciate relative to other currencies. When a currency appreciates, it means that it gains value compared to other currencies. This makes imports relatively more expensive and exports relatively less expensive, which can help to reduce the trade deficit.</div>", "topic": "INTERNATIONAL TRADE : EXCHANGE RATE"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The higher the dependency ratio the?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">larger the proportion of the employed relative to the unemployed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">smaller the proportion of the active labour force relative to the inactive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">smaller the number of the non-working age groups relative to the active labour force</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lower the birth rate</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The higher the dependency ratio, the smaller the proportion of the active labor force relative to the inactive. <br/>  <br/> The dependency ratio is a measure that compares the number of dependents (typically children and elderly individuals) to the number of individuals in the working-age population. It provides insights into the level of dependency on the working-age population to support and provide for dependents.</div>", "topic": "POPULATION : OVER POPULATION, UNDER POPULATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The age distribution of a country's population is of economic importance because it affects the?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pattern of expenditure</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">size of the army</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">optimum size of firms</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">location of industries</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The age distribution refers to the proportion of individuals in different age groups within a population. It provides insights into the demographic composition of a country's population. <br/>  <br/> For example, a higher proportion of elderly individuals might lead to increased demand for healthcare services, while a larger proportion of young individuals might drive demand for education and child-related products. Understanding the age distribution helps businesses and policymakers make informed decisions regarding resource allocation, investment, and market strategies based on the spending patterns of different age groups in the population.</div>", "topic": "POPULATION : THEORIES OF POPULATION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It is important to measure the National Income of a country because?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is a major determinant of the standard of living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it reveals hazards of development like pollution and congestion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it reveals the distribution of the citizen's savings in foreign banks</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its size determines the extent of political stability</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National income is a measure of the total value of goods and services produced within a country's borders over a specific period. It serves as a key indicator of the economic well-being and prosperity of a nation. <br/>  <br/> The level of national income plays a significant role in determining the standard of living, as it reflects the capacity of an economy to provide goods and services, income distribution, employment opportunities, and resources for public investment in areas such as education, healthcare, infrastructure, and social welfare.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : USES & REASONS FOR MEASURING NATIONAL INCOME"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Gross Domestic Product is defined as the total value of?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all final goods and services produced in a country during the year</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all assets of a country in a particular year</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exports net of total value of imports</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all receipts</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is defined as the total value of all final goods and services produced in a country during a specific period, typically a year. <br/>  <br/> It provides a comprehensive indicator of economic activity and is widely used to assess the size and growth of an economy.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the national income and product accounts, double counting is avoided if?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">only final goods are counted</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">only intermediate goods are counted</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">only intermediate and final goods are counted</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the value of all goods and services are added together</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Double counting refers to the potential issue of counting the value of a good or service more than once when calculating national income or GDP. This can happen if both intermediate goods (goods used in the production process) and final goods (goods intended for the end consumer) are included in the calculation. <br/>  <br/> To avoid double counting, only the value of final goods is counted in the national income and product accounts. Intermediate goods are not directly included in the calculation because their value is already accounted for in the final goods that they contribute to producing.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : MEASUREMENT OF NATIONAL INCOME"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">If W  stands for wages/salaries, P for profit, R for interest and Z for rent on land real estate, then national income is?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W-P-R-Z</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W+P+Z+R</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">P-R-Z-W</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W+P+R+Z</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">National income is calculated by summing the various components of income earned in an economy. These components include wages/salaries (W), profit (P), interest (R), and rent on land/real estate (Z). <br/>  <br/> Therefore, the correct expression for national income is W+P+R+Z which accurately represents the calculation of national income by summing the various income components using the income approach/method.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A major obstacle to economic development is?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a rise in industrial output</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">low farm productivity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">free trade</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ineffective trade unions</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Low farm productivity refers to the inefficiency or insufficient output of agricultural activities, including crop production and livestock farming. Agriculture is a crucial sector in many economies, particularly in developing countries, and plays a fundamental role in ensuring food security, providing employment, and contributing to overall economic growth.</div>", "topic": "ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT : INTRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> Consider the following diagram where XYZ represents the average curve of a firm. XY shows that as output increases the average declines. However, this decline cannot continue indefinitely because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">managerial economies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indivisibilities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the extent of the market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the pooling of dissimilar risks</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Indivisibilities refer to the concept that certain inputs or factors of production cannot be perfectly divisible or scaled down indefinitely. There are limits to how small or fragmented these inputs can be utilized in the production process. <br/>  <br/> In the context of the diagram, as the firm increases its output, there may come a point where the firm encounters indivisibilities in its production process. This means that the firm cannot further divide or scale down certain inputs, such as machinery, equipment, or specialized labor, to match the lower levels of output.</div>", "topic": "THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/>  <br/> The firm portrayed is selling in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a purely competitive market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a market in which demand elastic at all prices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an imperfectly competitive market</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a market in which companies produce homogeneous commodities</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The diagram indicates that the firm's average curve declines as output increases. This suggests that the firm is facing downward-sloping average revenue (AR) or demand curve, which is a characteristic of an imperfectly competitive market. <br/>  <br/> In an imperfectly competitive market, such as a monopolistic competition or oligopoly, firms have some degree of market power and can influence the price or quantity of their products. Unlike in a purely competitive market, where firms are price takers and face a perfectly elastic demand curve, an imperfectly competitive firm has the ability to affect the market price.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET-MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> Demand is relatively inelastic</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> range</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in the P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">4</span> price range</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at any price below P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the diagram, at price P2, the price falls to P1 which makes the quantity demanded to increase from Q2 to Q1 which represents inelastic demand curve (If demand is relatively inelastic, it means that changes in price have a relatively small impact on the quantity demanded. In other words, demand is less responsive to price changes.)  as shown in the diagram. <br/>  <br/> </div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following statements must hold if price discrimination is to be possible?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elasticities in the various markets must not differ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The seller must recognise the possibility of resale</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The market must not be separated but integrated</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The markets should be separable and there should be no resale</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Price discrimination occurs when a seller charges different prices to different consumers for the same product or service. For price discrimination to be possible, the markets in which the seller operates should be separable, meaning the seller can identify different groups of consumers with different price elasticities of demand and charge different prices to each group. Additionally, there should be no resale between these markets to prevent arbitrage, where consumers buy at a lower price in one market and resell at a higher price in another.</div>", "topic": "THE THEORY OF PRICE DETERMINATION : EFFECT OF CHANGE IN SUPPLY & DEMAND ON EQUILIBRIUM PRICE & QUANTITY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Q(tons)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 600</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 700</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 800</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 900</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 1000</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">TC(#)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 6800</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 8700</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 8400</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 9600</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 11000</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">MC(#/ton)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> </td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 10</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 6</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 12</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> 14</td></tr></table></div> <br/> Consider the table which shows output (O), total cost (TC) of production and marginal cost (MC) for a firm in a competitive market. Suppose price (P) = #12, what is the maximum profit the firm can make?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#2000</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#1200</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#1000</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#400</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Given: <br/> Price (P) = #12 <br/>  <br/> From the table, we can see that the marginal cost (MC) equals #12 at an output level of 900 tons. <br/>  <br/> Output (Q) = 900 tons <br/>  <br/> Now, to calculate total revenue (TR), we multiply the price (P) by the output (Q): <br/>  <br/> TR = P x Q <br/> = 12 x 900  <br/> = #10800 <br/>  <br/> Total Cost (TC) at 900 tons = #9600 (from the table) <br/>  <br/> Profit = Total Revenue - Total Cost <br/> = #10800 - #9600 <br/> = #1200</div>", "topic": "THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : THE MARGINAL COST & SUPPLY CURVE OF A FIRM"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/>  <br/> The excess profit made by the firm in the short-run is represented by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ORTZ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OPVY</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ORTW</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ORSX</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The diagram represents a perfect market making excess profit in the short run. From the diagram above, the excess or abnormal profit is represented as ORZ because the price is equal to its marginal cost (P = MC). </div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET-MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> The long-run equilibrium price and quantity for the firm are respectively</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OP, OY</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OR, OZ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OR, OX</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">OQ, OZ</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the long run, a perfect market makes only normal profit while abnormal profit is completely wipe off. Therefore, the equilibrium price and quantity are: OP and OY respectively.</div>", "topic": "MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET-MONOPOLY"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Stage of Product</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> Value of Input</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> Sale Value of Output</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Maize farmer</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">- </td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #10.00</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Flour miller</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #10.00</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #12.00</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Baker</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #12.00</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #15.00</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\">Shop keeper</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #15.00</td><td style=\"border:1px solid black;text-align:center;\"> #20.00</td></tr></table></div> <br/> The value of total output in the economy using the value approach is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#57.00</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#37.00</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#20.00</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">#15.00</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To calculate the value of total output using the value-added approach, we need to subtract the value of inputs from the sales value at each stage of production. <br/>  <br/> From the given information, the value added at each stage of production is as follows: <br/> Maize farmer: #10.00 - 0 = #10.00 <br/> Flour miller: #12.00 - #10.00 = #2.00 <br/> Baker: #15.00 - #12.00 = #3.00 <br/> Shopkeeper: #20.00 - #15.00 = #5.00 <br/>  <br/> To find the total output value using the value-added approach, we sum up these values: <br/>  <br/> Total output value = #10.00 + #2.00 + #3.00 + #5.00 <br/> = #20.00</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL INCOME : CONCEPT"}, {"id": "objective>Economics>1991>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In combining inputs x and y, the entrepreneur obtains the maximum output form a given money outlay when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span><hr size=\"1\" />MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span><hr size=\"1\" />MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span></td></tr></table></div></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span><hr size=\"1\" />P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span><hr size=\"1\" />P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span></td></tr></table></div></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span> . MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span> = P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span>. MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span> . P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span> = MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">x</span> . MP<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">y</span></div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To obtain the maximum output from a given money outlay when combining inputs x and y, the entrepreneur should allocate their money so that the marginal product of each input multiplied by its price is equal. This is known as the condition of equalizing the marginal product per unit of cost. <br/>  <br/> Px . MPx = Py . MPy. <br/> Px represents the price of input x. <br/> Py represents the price of input y. <br/> MPx represents the marginal product of input x (the additional output gained by using one more unit of x). <br/> MPy represents the marginal product of input y (the additional output gained by using one more unit of y). <br/> The entrepreneur wants to maximize output for a given money outlay. This means there's a fixed budget to spend on inputs x and y.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION"}];
